{"id":"2209.11307","submitter":"Kevin Grace","authors":"Sarah Allred, Craig Erickson, Kevin Grace, H. Tracy Hall, and Alathea\n  Jensen","title":"A combinatorial bound on the number of distinct eigenvalues of a graph","comments":"33 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The smallest possible number of distinct eigenvalues of a graph $G$, denoted\nby $q(G)$, has a combinatorial bound in terms of unique shortest paths in the\ngraph. In particular, $q(G)$ is bounded below by $k$, where $k$ is the number\nof vertices of a unique shortest path joining any pair of vertices in $G$.\nThus, if $n$ is the number of vertices of $G$, then $n-q(G)$ is bounded above\nby the size of the complement (with respect to the vertex set of $G$) of the\nvertex set of the longest unique shortest path joining any pair of vertices of\n$G$. The purpose of this paper is to commence the study of the minor-monotone\nfloor of $n-k$, which is the minimum of $n-k$ among all graphs of which $G$ is\na minor. Accordingly, we prove some results about this minor-monotone floor.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 22 Sep 2022 20:48:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-26"}
